  "topic_name": "Acids, Bases, and Salts",
  "canonical_explanation": {
    "text": "According to Arrhenius, acids produce H+ ions in water and bases produce OH- ions. Bronsted-Lowry theory defines acids as proton donors and bases as proton acceptors. The pH scale ranges from 0-14: pH 7 is neutral, below 7 is acidic, above 7 is basic. Strong acids (HCl, HNO3, H2SO4) completely dissociate; weak acids (CH3COOH, H2CO3) partially dissociate. Neutralization is the reaction between acid and base producing salt and water. Salts are classified as normal salts (all H+ replaced), acidic salts (some H+ remain), and basic salts (excess base).",
    "rules": [
      "Arrhenius: Acid produces H+, Base produces OH-",
      "Bronsted-Lowry: Acid is proton donor, Base is proton acceptor",
      "pH scale: 0-14; pH 7 = neutral; pH < 7 = acidic; pH > 7 = basic",
      "Strong acid: complete dissociation (HCl, HNO3, H2SO4)",
      "Weak acid: partial dissociation (CH3COOH, H2CO3)",
      "Neutralization: Acid + Base -> Salt + Water",
      "Indicators: Litmus, Methyl orange, Phenolphthalein"
    ]
  },
